# Session Viewer Development Prompt

Please utilize this prompt to generate a complete, actionable implementation plan for building the Session Viewer feature set described below. The deliverable should be implementation-ready across frontend, backend, and integration layers, with strong runtime safety (as mandated in the project context). Ensure all code paths guard against null/undefined values before array operations, use data ?? [] for Supabase results, and initialize state with proper defaults.

---

## Session Viewer

## Overview
Build a robust Session Viewer workflow that presents a detailed, transcript-driven view of a completed or in-progress session. It should surface the full transcript, extracted structured fields, collection timestamps, respondent metadata, and a feature-rich actions bar (export, resend to webhook, tag, annotate). The page must interoperate with declarative form field definitions and validation, a webhook dispatcher with retries and dead-lettering, an LLM orchestration engine, and session persistence/export capabilities. It should also support a replay mode that replays assistant messages and validation enforcement.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A dedicated Session Viewer page that shows a single session in depth: chronological transcript, each message with timestamp, model/prompts used, extracted structured fields, how/when fields were collected, and all associated respondent metadata. Actions include exporting the session (CSV/JSON), resending events to configured webhooks (with signing if configured), tagging, and annotating the session.

Goals:
- Provide a deterministic, auditable, end-to-end view of a session from ingestion through completion.
- Show the exact sequence of LLM interactions, including prompts and model identifiers.
- Display extracted fields with validation status, timestamps, and any server-side validation decisions.
- Provide actionable controls for operators (export, webhook re-send, tag/annotate, mark reviewed).
- Support a replay/trace mode to review how validations and knowledge lookups influenced assistant messages.

Connected features:
- Form Field Definition & Validation Engine: Declarative field definitions with deterministic server-side validations during sessions.
- Webhooks & External Integration Dispatcher: Reliable delivery to external endpoints with signing, retry strategy, and DLQ handling.
- LLM Orchestration & Conversation State Machine: Manages LLM calls, maintains per-session state, orchestrates knowledge lookups, routes messages to frontend, and streams live assistant messages.
- Session Persistence & Export: Persist all transcripts and structured fields; export support (CSV/JSON); scheduled/export bulk download capabilities.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Transcript Panel: Timeline-style transcript with messages, timestamps, model used, and prompts. Include streaming messages and replay indicators.
- Extracted Fields Table: Key-value pairs with per-field validation status, timestamps, and the source (user input, auto-extraction, validation result).
- Session Metadata: Collect timestamps, IP, user-agent, referrer, UTM tags, device/OS, browser details when available.
- Action Bar: Buttons for Export (CSV/JSON), Resend to Webhook, Tag, Annotate, Mark as Reviewed. Include status indicators (export progress, webhook delivery status).
- Replay Mode: A mode to replay streamed assistant messages and show decision points where validations were applied or knowledge lookups occurred.

Visual guidance:
- The page should inhabit a clean, card-based layout atop a light background, with a left/center content emphasis and a right-side actions module. Transcript and extracted fields should be primary panels; metadata and replay controls reside in secondary panels. Use the defined design system and color palette for consistency with the rest of the app.

---

## Components to Build
1. SessionViewerPage
   - Props: sessionId, userContext (optional), locale.
   - Responsibilities: fetch and render all session data; orchestrate child components; handle export and webhook resend actions; trigger replay mode.
2. TranscriptPanel
   - Data: Array of TranscriptMessage { id, timestamp, role, content, model, prompt, tokens }.
   - Features: live streaming appearance support, rebroadcast/replay controls, per-message metadata display.
3. ExtractedFieldsPanel
   - Data: Array of FieldDefinitionWithValue { fieldId, label, value, source, timestamp, validationStatus }.
   - Features: per-field status badges, sorting, filtering, and quick actions (tag/annotate from field).
4. SessionMetadataPanel
   - Data: Metadata object containing ip, ua, referrer, utm, device, geo, collectionTimestamps.
5. ActionBar
   - Actions: Export (CSV/JSON), ResendToWebhook, Tag, Annotate, MarkAsReviewed.
   - State: shows progress, last delivery status, error messages.
6. ReplayController
   - Responsibilities: navigate through streamed assistant messages, highlight validation gates, show decision points.
7. WebhookDispatcher (Server-Side)
   - Functions: dispatchSessionEvent(session), signPayloadIfConfigured(payload), implement retries with exponential backoff, DLQ persistence.
8. FieldValidationEngine (Server-Side)
   - Data: FieldDefinitions[]; ValidationRules[]; returns validated field set with statuses and messages.
9. LLMOrchestrator (Server-Side / Orchestrator Service)
   - Responsibilities: coordinate LLM calls, maintain per-session form state, knowledge lookups, validate inputs, stream assistant messages to frontend.
10. SessionPersistenceService
    - Responsibilities: Persist sessions to DB; ensure idempotency; support exportable formats.
11. ExportService
    - Responsibilities: Build CSV/JSON exports on demand or scheduled; ensure streaming for large sessions.
12. PublicChatPage (Agent URL)
    - Optional: Public chat interface for respondents; reuse SessionViewer read-only data with an input flow that collects required fields via natural dialogue.

All components must guard against nulls/undefined prior to array operations:
- Use (array ?? []).map(...) and Array.isArray(array) ? array.map(...) : []
- Supabase results must use data ?? [].
- Initialize React state as useState<T[]>([]) or useState<{...}[]>([]).
- Validate API shapes with const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- Optional chaining for nested API responses.
- Destructure with defaults where needed: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

